Title: Business Finland launches artificial intelligence programme | Science
Description: The objective of the new Business Finland programme, AI Business, is to make Finland the best country in the world to develop and utilise artificial intelligence and platform economy and to build global ecosystems and test platforms to attract investment. The AI Business program funds Finnish start-up, SME, midcap and large companies in all fields developing and utilising AI and platform economy in business. The programme also offers international networks and export services like matching selected companies with large global companies. The four-year AI Business programme’s (2018-2022) budget is EUR 200 million, of which Business Finland covers approximately half. In addition EUR 60 million can be used e.g. to fund digital platforms, resulting in significant network effects. Develop, test and invest in finland "Finland has decades of experience in neural network and artificial intelligence research, for example, and plenty of start-ups working together with research organisations. It has been estimated that artificial intelligence and platform economy will contribute 30 per cent to Finland's GDP in 2030. Business Finland's job is to share the risk of radical innovation development and thereby open the doors to selling them on the global market. Artificial intelligence and platform economy are just the things we want Finland to become the best place in the world to study, develop, test and invest. These are concrete measures to continue the valuable work of the artificial intelligence team set up by Minister Lintilä," says Business Finland's Director General Pekka Soini. AI Business also funds research especially in joint projects involving universities, research organisations and businesses. Global growth field Artificial intelligence is developing fast and it comes with limitless potential. Artificial intelligence can be used for customer service and as an invaluable source of information for diagnosis. One of the latest areas of application involves learning interfaces. When you can genuinely talk with digital services, the threshold for using them becomes much lower. The majority of platform economy funding goes to the development of B2B platforms and business ecosystems that create them. Finland is in an excellent position, especially together with other EU countries, to create new significant platforms. Up till now the field of platform economy has been dominated by US and Chinese companies. This release was first published on 5 February by Business Finland

Title: Artificial Intelligence | CFO Survey
Description:
Tomasz Konik has taken on the role of the Managing Partner at Deloitte Poland in June 2020 and has been with the firm for more than 20 years. Prior to becoming the Managing Partner at Deloitte Poland, he was Vice President of the Management Board in charge of the key clients and industry programs as the Clients & Industries Leader (since 2016) and successfully combined this role with responsibility for strategy and operations in Consulting (since 2017), which included human capital, change management, brand strategy, sustainable development, automation process and robotics advisory services. Between 2005 and 2017, he built and developed Deloitte’s tax teams in Katowice, Kraków, Rzeszów and Ostrava. Until 2005, he worked in the tax team at Deloitte’s office in Warsaw.
During his professional career, he was an attorney in fact in one of the first Polish tax cases heard before the European Court of Justice. As a result of its resolution, Polish laws were amended and brought into line with the laws of the European Union.
As the Managing Partner at Deloitte Poland, Tomasz continues to implement the firm’s strategy, one of the key priorities of which is for Deloitte to become an undisputed leader on the market of professional services, in line with the “Making an impact that matters” principle.
Tomasz is actively involved in social and non-profit initiatives – he is a LeadersIN mentor and a member of the Champions of Change Club, which brings together CEOs of the major companies in Poland with the objective to support professional development of women.
He is also a committed volunteer supporting, together with his family, holiday dinners for lonely people as well as Silesian equal opportunity organizations launching initiatives to take care of children from poor families in Katowice.
Tomasz graduated from the University of Economics in Katowice and completed an international MBA program at St. Gallen Business School. He also studied at IMD in Lausanne, Harvard Business School and IESE in Barcelona. He has been a licensed tax adviser since 2004.
Tomasz Konik is also a loving husband and a devoted father of two girls. He spends his leisure time actively, travelling around the world, running and mountain climbing. ​
